"title": "5710: marriage, customs concerning",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5710: marriage, customs concerning",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Marriage between two individuals united their families and involved the whole community. Parents, particularly fathers, took an active part in selecting partners for their children. There was often a long period of betrothal; wedding celebrations were usually elaborate and might last a week or more.</p>\n<h2>The choice of a marriage partner</h2>\n<h3>Parents usually chose a suitable partner</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen38:6\">GEN 38:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:2-Gen24:4\">GEN 24:2–24:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen21:21\">GEN 21:21</a> <em>Occasionally mothers made the wedding arrangements.</em></p>\n<h3>The wishes of the couple</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:57-Gen24:58\">GEN 24:57–24:58</a></strong> <em>Rebekah is consulted about her proposed marriage to Isaac.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen34:4\">GEN 34:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen34:8-Gen34:9\">GEN 34:8–34:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg14:2\">JDG 14:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam18:20\">1SA 18:20</a></p>\n<h2>The bride-price</h2>\n<h3>Daughters were ``given'' by their fathers</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:28\">GEN 29:28</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod2:21\">EXO 2:21</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam18:21\">1SA 18:21</a></p>\n<h3>Fathers often received payment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:18\">GEN 29:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen34:12\">GEN 34:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:30\">GEN 29:30</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod22:16-Exod22:17\">EXO 22:16–22:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut22:28-Deut22:29\">DEU 22:28–22:29</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam18:17\">1SA 18:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam18:27\">1SA 18:27</a></p>\n<h3>Daughters were given as a reward</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg1:12-Judg1:13\">JDG 1:12–1:13</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh15:16-Josh15:17\">JOS 15:16–15:17</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam18:25\">1SA 18:25</a></p>\n<h2>The exchange of wedding gifts</h2>\n<h3>Gifts from the bridegroom's family</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:53\">GEN 24:53</a></p>\n<h3>Gifts from the bride's father</h3>\n<p>Servants given to the bride as a dowry:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:59\">GEN 24:59</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:24\">GEN 29:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:29\">GEN 29:29</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg1:14-Judg1:15\">JDG 1:14–1:15</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh15:18-Josh15:19\">JOS 15:18–15:19</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs9:16\">1KI 9:16</a></p>\n<h2>The period of betrothal</h2>\n<h3>Betrothal followed payment of the bride-price</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam3:14\">2SA 3:14</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:19-Gen29:20\">GEN 29:19–29:20</a> <em>Jacob worked for Laban during his period of betrothal to Rachel.</em></p>\n<h3>A betrothed couple were regarded as husband and wife</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen19:14\">GEN 19:14</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut22:23-Deut22:24\">DEU 22:23–22:24</a> <em>Unfaithfulness during the period of betrothal is treated as adultery</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt1:18-Matt1:20\">MAT 1:18–1:20</a> <em>Divorce is required to break a betrothal.</em></p>\n<h3>Sexual relationships took place only after the wedding</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:21\">GEN 29:21</a></strong> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Joel1:8\">JOL 1:8</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:27\">LUK 1:27</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt1:25\">MAT 1:25</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor7:36-1Cor7:38\">1CO 7:36–7:38</a></p>\n<h2>Soldiers and marriage</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut20:7\">DEU 20:7</a> <em>Engaged soldiers were to marry before going into battle</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut24:5\">DEU 24:5</a> <em>Recently married soldiers were exempted from military service for a year.</em></p>\n<h2>The wedding celebrations</h2>\n<h3>The bride wore an elaborate dress and jewellery</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:9-Ezek16:13\">EZK 16:9–16:13</a></strong> <em>An allegorical description of God dressing Jerusalem as a bride.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps45:13\">PSA 45:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa61:10\">ISA 61:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:32\">JER 2:32</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:2\">REV 21:2</a></p>\n<h3>Attendants on the bride and groom</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps45:14\">PSA 45:14</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:29\">JHN 3:29</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg14:11\">JDG 14:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg14:20\">JDG 14:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt9:15\">MAT 9:15</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:19\">MRK 2:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:34\">LUK 5:34</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt25:1-Matt25:10\">MAT 25:1–25:10</a></p>\n<h3>The wedding banquet</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:22\">GEN 29:22</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg14:10\">JDG 14:10</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:2\">MAT 22:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev19:9\">REV 19:9</a></p>\n<h3>Wedding festivities</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps78:63\">PSA 78:63</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:5\">ISA 62:5</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer7:34\">JER 7:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer33:11\">JER 33:11</a></p>\n<h3>The invitation to a wedding</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:3-Matt22:4\">MAT 22:3–22:4</a> <em>Invited guests were called when the feast was ready.</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:5-Matt22:7\">MAT 22:5–22:7</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke14:18-Luke14:21\">LUK 14:18–14:21</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:11-Matt22:12\">MAT 22:11–22:12</a> <em>Guests were expected to dress appropriately.</em></p>",
